>>61804177
NTA, and I have no way of saying this nicely. It's disjointed and there's a focus on giving details that don't help the reader get invested, then either skipping or skimming over information that would get the reader invested.

Your first chapter is vital, it doesn't matter if you've got some fantastic story planned out if the introduction is confusingly messy, doesn't introduce things well, or keeps giving details your eyes want to gloss over because you don't know who these people are or what is going on.

Establish who the reader should care about and what is going on. If a reader is having to go back and check if there are details they missed, you're not doing a good job. This has serious vibes of you know what is going on, so you want to get moving along or add vivid details, but you're forgotten people can't read your mind only what you write. Happy_dragon has a similar problem, but with better grammar.

>>61806061
There are links in the OP under Writing Guides but I can't swear by any of the resources. Most of learning to write is making the mistakes and improving as your understanding deepens.

I promise you, no one minds if you post a revised version. If it makes you feel any better, it's completely normal to start over. If you feel discouraged at all, I highly recommend making a short story or vignette. Set a low word or page count and try not to go over it. It can be finished in a reasonable time period and it's also a lot easier to get critique or advice on a complete idea.

I can't stress this enough, but read. Not even necessarily in the genre you want to write, but so you can understand how other people do it. Developing an eye for how stories are put together can be a task, but it pays off.

If there are any writers you like, try getting in contact with them. Ask how they do things, how they wrote one of their stories you liked, what inspired them, that sort of brain picking. Maybe you've got common interests, maybe they don't respond, but never underestimate a good network when you make things.
